{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505126"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2406"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2406"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.77,0.03,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53439"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2406"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38905"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4113"},{"type":"tags","id":"4114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44671"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53439"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting contraception. She is sexually active with her long-term male partner and uses condoms intermittently. She has no plans to become pregnant in the future and wants a form of contraceptive that helps with her heavy menstrual bleeding. She has regular menstrual cycles with normal to heavy flow for the first three days. She wishes to avoid visiting the GP clinic regularly for renewal of any contraceptive medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a medical history of epilepsy and currently takes carbamazepine 400 mg twice daily. She has no other significant medical history and is nulliparous. There is no family history of breast cancer. She smokes two to three cigarettes per day for the past four years and drinks two standard drinks per day. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her physical examination is unremarkable and her urine pregnancy test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate contraceptive method?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Copper intrauterine device","Levonorgestrel-releasing intrauterine system","Combined oral contraceptive pill","Medroxyprogesterone acetate depot injection","Etonogestrel implant"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis 25-year-old woman is seeking long-term contraception that will also help manage her heavy menstrual bleeding. It is important to note that she takes carbamazepine which induces cytochrome P450 enzymes in the liver, increasing the metabolism and clearance of oestrogen and progestogen hormones. This reduces the efficacy of any oral hormonal contraceptives as well as progesterone implants. Effective contraception is especially important for this patient as carbamazepine is teratogenic and associated with an increased risk of neural tube defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate option for her is a \u003Cstrong\u003Elevonorgestrel-releasing intrauterine system\u003C/strong\u003E (IUS) such as Mirena. It provides effective contraception for up to eight years and fertility returns rapidly after removal of the IUS. The Mirena would be preferred over the Kyleena due to the greater reduction in menorrhagia, up to 90%. Its efficacy is not affected by the enzyme-inducing antiepileptic medication carbamazepine that she is taking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecopper intrauterine device\u003C/strong\u003E would also provide long-term contraception but may worsen heavy menstrual bleeding, making it less suitable for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in women taking enzyme-inducing medications like carbamazepine as it reduces the contraceptive efficacy. It also requires regular GP visits for prescription renewal which the patient wishes to avoid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedroxyprogesterone acetate depot injections\u003C/strong\u003E provide effective contraception for three months at a time, but require regular clinic visits which the patient wants to minimise. They can also cause irregular bleeding and delayed return to fertility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eetonogestrel implant\u003C/strong\u003E (Implanon) is a long-acting reversible contraceptive that is usually highly effective. However, its efficacy is reduced by enzyme-inducing medications like carbamazepine. Additionally, it may not adequately address the patient\u0027s heavy menstrual bleeding, as it can cause unpredictable bleeding patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intrauterine contraceptive devices can provide long-term contraception and have few side effects.","Carbamazepine is an enzyme-inducing medication that can reduce the efficacy of some hormonal contraceptives."],"references":["Buhling KJ, Zite NB, Lotke P, et al. Worldwide use of intrauterine contraception: A review. Contraception. 2014;89:162. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24369300/","Rivera R, Yacobson I, Grimes D. The mechanism of action of hormonal contraceptives and intrauterine contraceptive devices. Am J Obstet Gynecol 1999;181:1263. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10561657/","Stanford JB, Mikolajczyk RT. Mechanisms of action of intrauterine devices: Update and estimation of postfertilization effects. Am J Obstet Gynecol 2002;187:1699. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12501086/","Hormonal IUD available in Australia Comparison Chart. In: Victoria: Sexual Health Victoria [online].  2022 [Updated 2022 Feb; cited 2023 Jul 7]. Available at: https://shvic.org.au/assets/img/content/Hormonal-IUDs-available-in-Australia-comparison-chart-for-prescribers-and-IUD-inserters-TOOLS.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38905"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2406"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38905"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-21T13:29:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-21T13:30:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2406"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53439"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"att